    👨‍🏫 2. EXPLAINING TO A PRO ( PRO LEVEL)

    Now we go deeper 👇
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------   
    
    🧠 SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE

    This is a full-stack application:

        .Frontend: React (UI + user interaction)
        .Backend: Node.js + Express (API layer)
        .Database: PostgreSQL
        .ORM: Sequelize

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
   
    🔄 FULL DATA FLOW

    1. Frontend Layer (React)

        .Manages UI and state using useState
        .Captures user input via controlled inputs
        .Sends HTTP requests using Axios

        👉 Example actions:
        .POST /api/events
        .GET /api/events
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    2. API Layer (Express)

    Routes handle requests:

    POST /api/events
        .Receives request body:
            .name
            .organizerName
            .venueName
            .capacity
        .Creates:
            .Organizer record
            .Venue record
            .Event record with foreign keys
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    3. ORM Layer (Sequelize)
        .Converts JavaScript operations into SQL queries
        .Manages relationships using:
                .belongsTo
                .hasMany
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------        
    
    🧩 DATABASE DESIGN (NORMALIZATION)

            Tables:

            Organizers
                .id
                .name
            Venues
                .id
                .name
                .capacity
            Events
                .id
                .name
                .OrganizerId (FK)
                .VenueId (FK)

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    
    🔗 RELATIONSHIPS

        .Event "belongsTo" Organizer
        .Event "belongsTo" Venue
        .Organizer "hasMany" Events
        .Venue "hasMany" Events

    👉 This ensures:

        .No duplicated data
        .Clean structure
        .Scalability

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------        
    
    📡 GET /api/events
    
        .Uses Sequelize include:

        javascript......|include: [Organizer, Venue]|..............

        👉 This performs a SQL JOIN behind the scenes
        
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

        🔁 RESPONSE STRUCTURE

            Backend returns:

            {
            "name": "Concert",
            "Organizer": { "name": "RBA" },
            "Venue": { "name": "Camp Kigali", "capacity": 100 }
            }

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    🎨 FRONTEND DATA MAPPING

        React accesses nested data:
            .event.Organizer.name
            .event.Venue.name

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    📁 WHAT EACH FILE DOES

    🔹 server.js
        .Entry point of backend
        .Defines routes (GET, POST, DELETE)
        .Connects everything together

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------        

    🔹 models/
        .Defines database structure

        Event.js
         .Event table

        Organizer.js
            .Organizer table

        Venue.js
            .Venue table

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------            

    🔹 models/index.js
        .Central place for:
        .Importing models
        .Defining relationships
👉 This is where associations live

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    🔹 config/db.js
        .Connects to PostgreSQL database

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------    
    🔹 App.jsx (Frontend)
        .Handles:
            .UI rendering
            .Form state
            .API calls
            .Table display

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    ⚙️ HOW EVERYTHING CONNECTS
    User → React (form)
        → Axios (HTTP request)
        → Express (route)
        → Sequelize (ORM)
        → PostgreSQL (database)

    Then back:

    Database → Sequelize → Express → React → UI

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    🎯 FINAL PROFESSIONAL EXPLANATION

    👉 Lets say this:

    “The application follows a full-stack architecture where the React frontend communicates
     with an Express backend through RESTful APIs. Sequelize ORM is used to map JavaScript 
     models to a PostgreSQL relational database. The system is normalized into separate 
     entities—Events, Organizers, and Venues—with relationships defined using foreign keys. 
    Data flows from the UI to the backend, where it is processed, stored, and then retrieved 
    using JOIN operations before being displayed back on the frontend.”

